Commitment discounts, Reserved Instances, Savings Plans, and Spot.

For anything running steadily, paying On-Demand is leaving thirty to seventy percent on the table, and A-W-S offers three families of discount.

Reserved Instances, or R-Is, mean you commit to a specific instance family and region for one or three years, for up to about seventy-two percent off On-Demand. Standard R-Is give the deepest discount but are locked to the exact family; Convertible R-Is give a smaller discount but can be exchanged for different families during the term. They're best for predictable steady-state on a single family. Savings Plans, or S-Ps, mean you commit to an hourly dollar amount of spend, and the discount applies across families and regions automatically. Compute Savings Plans cover E-C-2, Fargate, and Lambda interchangeably and are the most flexible; E-C-2 Instance Savings Plans are pinned to a family but slightly deeper. S-Ps are much easier to manage than R-Is for fleets that churn across families. And Spot Instances let you bid on unused E-C-2 capacity for up to about ninety percent off, but A-W-S can reclaim the instance with a two-minute notice, so they're perfect for batch jobs, C-I runners, stateless workers, and Fargate Spot, and never for a stateful database.

The standard layering is a stack. The always-on baseline goes on Savings Plans or R-Is. Variable but steady load picks up additional Savings Plans as it stabilises. Burst and fault-tolerant work runs on Spot. And the spiky, unpredictable tip stays On-Demand. The rule: commit on the base, burst on Spot, and pay On-Demand only for the unpredictable tip. On R-Is versus S-Ps, if you need cross-family flexibility, choose Savings Plans; if you need a specific reserved-capacity guarantee in an Availability Zone, choose zonal R-Is.
